OpenMaui's architecture separates rendering logic from platform integration, making unit testing straightforward. With 217 passing unit tests using xUnit, Moq, and FluentAssertions, the project demonstrates comprehensive test coverage for Skia-based views and handlers.

## Testing View Rendering Logic

Skia views like `SkiaButton`, `SkiaLabel`, and `SkiaEntry` contain rendering logic that should be tested independently of the windowing system. Focus your tests on:

**Property mapping and updates:**
```csharp
[Fact]
public void SkiaButton_TextProperty_UpdatesRendering()
{
    var button = new SkiaButton();
    button.Text = "Click Me";

    Assert.Equal("Click Me", button.Text);
    Assert.True(button.IsDirty); // Dirty flag triggers redraw
}
```

**Visual state management:**
```csharp
[Fact]
public void SkiaButton_PressedState_ChangesAppearance()
{
    var button = new SkiaButton
    {
        BackgroundColor = Colors.Blue
    };

    button.SetVisualState(VisualStates.Pressed);

    // Verify visual state affects rendering
    Assert.NotEqual(Colors.Blue, button.CurrentBackgroundColor);
}
```

**Layout calculations:**
```csharp
[Fact]
public void SkiaGrid_MeasureAndArrange_CalculatesCorrectBounds()
{
    var grid = new SkiaGrid
    {
        RowDefinitions = new RowDefinitionCollection
        {
            new RowDefinition { Height = GridLength.Auto },
            new RowDefinition { Height = new GridLength(1, GridUnitType.Star) }
        }
    };

    var size = grid.Measure(new Size(400, 600));
    grid.Arrange(new Rect(0, 0, 400, 600));

    Assert.Equal(400, grid.Width);
    Assert.Equal(600, grid.Height);
}
```

## Testing Handler Implementations

Handlers bridge MAUI controls to platform views. Test that property mappers correctly translate MAUI properties to Skia view properties:

```csharp
[Fact]
public void ButtonHandler_TextProperty_MapsToSkiaButton()
{
    var mauiButton = new Button { Text = "Test" };
    var handler = new ButtonHandler();
    handler.SetVirtualView(mauiButton);

    var skiaButton = handler.PlatformView as SkiaButton;

    Assert.NotNull(skiaButton);
    Assert.Equal("Test", skiaButton.Text);
}

[Fact]
public void EntryHandler_TextChangedEvent_FiresCorrectly()
{
    var mauiEntry = new Entry();
    var handler = new EntryHandler();
    handler.SetVirtualView(mauiEntry);

    string changedText = null;
    mauiEntry.TextChanged += (s, e) => changedText = e.NewTextValue;

    var skiaEntry = handler.PlatformView as SkiaEntry;
    skiaEntry.Text = "New Text";
    skiaEntry.RaiseTextChanged();

    Assert.Equal("New Text", changedText);
}
```

## Mocking Platform Services

Use Moq to isolate platform services during testing:

```csharp
[Fact]
public async Task FilePicker_PickAsync_ReturnsSelectedFile()
{
    var mockDialogService = new Mock<ILinuxDialogService>();
    mockDialogService
        .Setup(x => x.ShowFilePickerAsync(It.IsAny<FilePickerOptions>()))
        .ReturnsAsync("/home/user/document.pdf");

    var filePicker = new LinuxFilePicker(mockDialogService.Object);
    var result = await filePicker.PickAsync();

    Assert.NotNull(result);
    Assert.Equal("document.pdf", result.FileName);
}
```

## Test Organization

Organize tests by component type:
- `Tests/Views/` - Skia view rendering and behavior
- `Tests/Handlers/` - Handler property mapping and events
- `Tests/Services/` - Platform service implementations
- `Tests/Layout/` - Layout container measure and arrange logic

With 217 passing unit tests covering views, services, and handlers, OpenMaui demonstrates that comprehensive testing is achievable even for complex platform implementations.

Unit tests verify logic, but integration tests ensure your application works correctly with X11, Wayland, and different desktop environments. These tests require actual display servers and window managers.

## Setting Up Test Environments

**Xvfb for headless X11 testing:**
```bash
# Install Xvfb (X Virtual Frame Buffer)
sudo apt-get install xvfb

# Run tests with virtual display
xvfb-run -a dotnet test

# With specific resolution and color depth
xvfb-run -a -s "-screen 0 1920x1080x24" dotnet test
```

**Wayland testing with weston:**
```bash
# Install weston compositor
sudo apt-get install weston

# Run tests in weston environment
weston --backend=headless-backend.so &
export WAYLAND_DISPLAY=wayland-0
dotnet test
```

## Window Lifecycle Tests

Test window creation, showing, hiding, and destruction:

```csharp
[Fact]
public void LinuxWindow_CreateAndShow_DisplaysCorrectly()
{
    var app = new LinuxApplication();
    var window = new LinuxWindow(app)
    {
        Title = "Test Window",
        Width = 800,
        Height = 600
    };

    window.Show();
    app.ProcessEvents(); // Process pending X11/Wayland events

    Assert.True(window.IsVisible);
    Assert.Equal(800, window.Width);
    Assert.Equal(600, window.Height);

    window.Close();
}
```

## Rendering Pipeline Tests

Verify the SkiaSharp rendering pipeline works with actual GPU contexts:

```csharp
[Fact]
public void GpuRenderingEngine_Initialize_CreatesOpenGLContext()
{
    var window = new GtkHostWindow();
    window.Show();

    var renderEngine = new GpuRenderingEngine(window);
    var initialized = renderEngine.Initialize();

    Assert.True(initialized);
    Assert.NotNull(renderEngine.GRContext);
    Assert.True(renderEngine.SupportsHardwareAcceleration);

    window.Close();
}

[Fact]
public void SkiaRenderingEngine_DirtyRegion_OptimizesRedraws()
{
    var surface = CreateTestSurface(800, 600);
    var engine = new SkiaRenderingEngine(surface);

    var button = new SkiaButton
    {
        Bounds = new Rect(10, 10, 100, 40)
    };

    engine.AddView(button);
    engine.Render(); // Initial full render

    button.Text = "Updated";
    var dirtyRect = engine.GetDirtyRegion();

    // Only button region should be dirty
    Assert.Equal(new Rect(10, 10, 100, 40), dirtyRect);
}
```

## Multi-Monitor Tests

Test HiDPI scaling and multi-monitor configurations:

```csharp
[Fact]
public void LinuxWindow_HiDPIDisplay_ScalesCorrectly()
{
    var window = new LinuxWindow(new LinuxApplication());
    var scaleFactor = window.GetScaleFactor();

    window.Width = 800;
    window.Height = 600;

    // Physical pixels should account for scale factor
    Assert.Equal(800 * scaleFactor, window.PhysicalWidth);
    Assert.Equal(600 * scaleFactor, window.PhysicalHeight);
}
```

## Input Method Editor (IME) Tests

Test text input with IBus, Fcitx5, and XIM:

```csharp
[Fact]
public void SkiaEntry_IMEInput_HandlesComposition()
{
    var entry = new SkiaEntry();
    var imeContext = new LinuxIMEContext(entry);

    // Simulate IME composition
    imeContext.SetCompositionText("こんにちは");
    Assert.Equal("こんにちは", entry.CompositionText);

    // Commit composition
    imeContext.CommitComposition();
    Assert.Equal("こんにちは", entry.Text);
    Assert.Null(entry.CompositionText);
}
```

## Theme Detection Tests

Verify system theme detection across desktop environments:

```csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData("GNOME", "Adwaita-dark")]
[InlineData("KDE", "Breeze-Dark")]
public void SystemThemeService_DetectDarkMode_ReturnsCorrectTheme(
    string desktopEnv, string themeName)
{
    Environment.SetEnvironmentVariable("XDG_CURRENT_DESKTOP", desktopEnv);
    Environment.SetEnvironmentVariable("GTK_THEME", themeName);

    var themeService = new SystemThemeService();
    var isDark = themeService.IsDarkMode();

    Assert.True(isDark);
}
```

## Continuous Integration Setup

Configure GitHub Actions for automated integration testing:

```yaml
name: Integration Tests

on: [push, pull_request]

jobs:
  test:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v3

      - name: Setup .NET
        uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v3
        with:
          dotnet-version: '8.0.x'

      - name: Install dependencies
        run: |
          sudo apt-get update
          sudo apt-get install -y xvfb libgtk-3-0 libwebkit2gtk-4.0-37

      - name: Run integration tests
        run: xvfb-run -a dotnet test --filter Category=Integration
```

Integration tests catch issues that unit tests miss: display server compatibility, font rendering with HarfBuzz, gesture recognition accuracy, and theme application consistency.

Developing on Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL) offers convenience, but debugging production issues often requires native Linux environments. Understanding the differences helps you debug effectively in both contexts.

## WSL Development Setup

WSL 2 with WSLg provides GUI support for Linux applications:

```bash
# Check WSL version
wsl --version

# Ensure WSL 2 is enabled
wsl --set-default-version 2

# Install Ubuntu
wsl --install -d Ubuntu-22.04
```

**Install development dependencies:**
```bash
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y dotnet-sdk-8.0 libgtk-3-0 libwebkit2gtk-4.0-37 \
  libharfbuzz0b libfontconfig1 libfreetype6
```

## Visual Studio Code Remote Development

Configure VS Code for WSL debugging:

